  1. For the year 2018, calculate the average PM2.5 concentration for each season (Seasons being Winter: December-February, Summer: March-May, and Monsoon: June-September)

for stations Lal Bahadur Shastri Nagar, Kalaburagi - KSPCB. Identifying the season with the highest pollution.

df2['Timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Timestamp'])

#df_2018 = df2[(df2['Timestamp'].dt.year == 2018) & (df2['station'] == "Lal Bahadur Shastri Nagar, Kalaburagi - KSPCB")]
#is a risky way because df_2018 becomes a view of the original file then, modifying df_2018 changes df2 also therefore,
df_2018 = df2[(df2['Timestamp'].dt.year == 2018) & (df2['station'] == "Lal Bahadur Shastri Nagar, Kalaburagi - KSPCB")].copy()

df_2018['month'] = df_2018['Timestamp'].dt.month

def get_season(month):
    if month in [12, 1, 2]:  # Winter
        return 'Winter'
    elif month in [3, 4, 5]:  # Summer
        return 'Summer'
    elif month in [6, 7, 8, 9]:  # Monsoon
        return 'Monsoon'
    else:
        return 'Other'


df_2018['season'] = df_2018['Timestamp'].dt.month.apply(get_season)
#print(df_2018[df_2018['season'] == 'Summer']['PM2.5'].isna().sum()) gives 92
#found that there are only NaN values for the summer season

seasonal_avg_pm25 = df_2018.groupby('season')['PM2.5'].mean()

# most_polluted_season = seasonal_avg_pm25.idxmax()
# but there might be 2 seasons having highest PM2.5, therefore
most_polluted_seasons = seasonal_avg_pm25[seasonal_avg_pm25 == seasonal_avg_pm25.max()].index
print(most_polluted_seasons.tolist())# tolist() gives a standard Python list instead of a Pandas object.

print("Average PM2.5 concentration per season in 2018:")
print(seasonal_avg_pm25)
print("\nSeason with the highest PM2.5 concentration:", most_polluted_seasons)

df_2021 = df2[(df2['Timestamp'].dt.year == 2021) &
              (df2['station'] == "Lal Bahadur Shastri Nagar, Kalaburagi - KSPCB")].copy()

df_2021['month'] = df_2021['Timestamp'].dt.month
df_2021['day_of_week'] = df_2021['Timestamp'].dt.dayofweek  #Note: Monday=0, Sunday=6

df_2021['day_type'] = df_2021['day_of_week'].apply(lambda x: 'Weekday' if x < 5 else 'Weekend')

monthly_avg_pm25 = df_2021.groupby(['month', 'day_type'])['PM2.5'].mean().unstack()
#note the very imp function in prev line, .unstack() used to convert groupby row to column

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))

plt.plot(monthly_avg_pm25.index, monthly_avg_pm25['Weekday'], marker='o', linestyle='-', label='Weekdays', color='b')
plt.plot(monthly_avg_pm25.index, monthly_avg_pm25['Weekend'], marker='s', linestyle='--', label='Weekends', color='r')

# Formatting the graph
plt.xticks(range(1, 13), ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])
plt.xlabel("Month")
plt.ylabel("Average PM2.5")
plt.title("Monthly Average PM2.5 (Weekdays vs. Weekends) - 2021")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

plt.show()

Spatio-temporal aggregation [3 marks]¶

  1. For each state, calculate the percentage increase or decrease in PM2.5 levels during monsoon months (June to September) compared to summer months (March to May). Which state has the most difference (increase or decrease) for the year 2022?
In [3]:
df= pd.read_csv('Data.csv')
state=pd.read_csv('State_data.csv')
NCAP=pd.read_csv('NCAP_Funding.csv')

df['Timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Timestamp'], errors='coerce')
df_2022 = df[df['Timestamp'].dt.year == 2022]
df_2022['Month'] = df_2022['Timestamp'].dt.month
summer_months = [3, 4, 5] 
monsoon_months = [6, 7, 8, 9]
df_2022_pm25 = df_2022[['PM2.5', 'Month', 'state']].dropna(subset=['PM2.5'])
monthly_avg_pm25 = df_2022_pm25.groupby(['state', 'Month']).agg({'PM2.5': 'mean'}).reset_index()
summer_data = monthly_avg_pm25[monthly_avg_pm25['Month'].isin(summer_months)]
monsoon_data = monthly_avg_pm25[monthly_avg_pm25['Month'].isin(monsoon_months)]
summer_avg = summer_data.groupby('state')['PM2.5'].mean()
monsoon_avg = monsoon_data.groupby('state')['PM2.5'].mean()
seasonal_avg = pd.merge(summer_avg, monsoon_avg, on='state', suffixes=('_summer', '_monsoon'))
seasonal_avg['percentage_change'] = ((seasonal_avg['PM2.5_monsoon'] - seasonal_avg['PM2.5_summer']) / seasonal_avg['PM2.5_summer']) * 100
max_change_state = seasonal_avg.loc[seasonal_avg['percentage_change'].abs().idxmax()]
print("State with the highest PM2.5 difference in 2022:")
print(max_change_state)

delhi_data = df[df['city'] == 'Delhi']
delhi_data['Timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(delhi_data['Timestamp'])
delhi_data['Year'] = delhi_data['Timestamp'].dt.year
delhi_data['Month'] = delhi_data['Timestamp'].dt.month
def assign_season(month):
    if month in [12, 1, 2]:  
        return 'Winter'
    elif month in [3, 4, 5]:  
        return 'Summer'
    elif month in [6, 7, 8, 9]:  
        return 'Monsoon'
delhi_data['Season'] = delhi_data['Month'].apply(assign_season)
seasonal_avg = delhi_data.groupby(['Year', 'Season'])['PM2.5'].mean().reset_index()
seasonal_avg_pivot = seasonal_avg.pivot(index='Year', columns='Season', values='PM2.5')
seasonal_avg_pivot.plot(kind='line', marker='o')
plt.title('Average PM2.5 Levels for Delhi (2017-2023) Across Seasons')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Average PM2.5 (µg/m³)')
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend(title='Season')
plt.xticks(seasonal_avg_pivot.index, rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

df_population = pd.read_csv("State_data (2).csv")
df_PM2_5 = pd.read_csv("Data (2).csv")

df_population.rename(columns=lambda x: x.strip().lower(), inplace=True)
df_PM2_5.rename(columns=lambda x: x.strip().lower(), inplace=True)

df_PM2_5 ["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df_PM2_5["timestamp"])
date_2023 = df_PM2_5 [df_PM2_5 ["date"].dt.year == 2023]
date_2023 = date_2023.groupby("state")["pm2.5"].mean()
merged_df = pd.merge(df_population,date_2023, on="state", how="inner")


merged_df["per_capita_pm2.5"] = merged_df["pm2.5"] / merged_df["population"]
merged_df.sort_values("per_capita_pm2.5",ascending = False)

# Get the top 5 states with the highest per capita PM2.5 exposure
top_5_polluted = merged_df.head(5)

# Display the results
print("Top 5 Most Polluted States (Per Capita PM2.5 Exposure):")
print(top_5_polluted[["state", "per_capita_pm2.5"]])

# Plot the results
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x="state", y="per_capita_pm2.5", data = top_5_polluted, palette="Reds")
plt.xlabel("State")

import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from shapely.geometry import Point

# Path to the extracted shapefile you downloaded from Natural Earth
shapefile_path = r"C:\Users\prabhanshu chouhan\Downloads\110m_cultural\ne_110m_admin_0_countries.shp"

# Load the shapefile using GeoPandas
world = gpd.read_file(shapefile_path)

# Filter the world data to get India
india = world[world['ADMIN'] == 'India']  # Replace 'ADMIN' with the correct column name

# Extract sensor locations from your provided dataframe (latitude and longitude)
sensor_locations = df[['latitude', 'longitude']].dropna()  # Ensure no missing coordinates
sensor_locations = [Point(lon, lat) for lat, lon in zip(sensor_locations['latitude'], sensor_locations['longitude'])]

# Create a GeoDataFrame for sensor locations
gdf_sensors = gpd.GeoDataFrame(geometry=sensor_locations)

# Plotting the map of India
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))  # Set figure size
india.plot(ax=ax, color='lightgray')  # Plot India in light gray

# Plotting the sensor locations on the map
gdf_sensors.plot(ax=ax, color='red', markersize=50, label='Sensor Locations')

# Adding labels and title
plt.title('Map of India with Sensor Locations')
plt.xlabel('Longitude')
plt.ylabel('Latitude')

# Show the legend
plt.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Tell us something new [1 Mark]¶

Tell us something interesting from the dataset that we have not asked. Anything that intrigues you, anything that might be useful to the policymakers.

The relationship between PM2.5 and PM10 has not been asked in the questions By analyzing the correlation between these pollutants, policymakers can better identify the common sources of pollution and implement more efficient measures targeting both. By knowing the strength of the relationship between PM2.5 and PM10, regulation of industrial emissions, transportation policies, and air quality monitoring can be adjusted to maximize health benefits and environmental improvements.
